{"title_page": "Bangladesh Development Bank", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Bangladesh Development Bank Limited\n| logo = Bangladesh_Development_Bank_Limited_LOGO.png\n| type = [[National bank|State owned bank]]\n| Extent of Shareholding = 100% share owned by the Government of Bangladesh\n| num_locations    = 46\n| key_people = {{Unbulleted list | Mohammad Mejbahuddin ([[Chairman]]) | kazi Alamgir([[Managing Director|MD]])}}\n| industry = [[International financial institutions|Development Bank]]<br />[[Bank]]<br />[[Capital Markets]] and allied industries\n| products = [[Retail banking]], [[Private banking]], [[Commercial bank|Corporate Banking]], [[Deposit (finance)|Deposits]], [[Mortgage loan]], Savings Scheme, Sanchay Scheme, Trade and Retail Forex\n| revenue = \n| net_income = \n| assets = {{BDTConvert|54.55|b|lk=yes}}\n| num_employees = About 775\n| foundation = [[Dhaka]], 16 November 2009\n| location = |\n| homepage = {{URL|www.bdbl.com.bd}}\n}}\n\n'''Bangladesh Development Bank''' (Bengali: \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09a1\u09c7\u09ad\u09c7\u09b2\u09aa\u09ae\u09c7\u09a8\u09cd\u099f \u09ac\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u0982\u0995 \u09b2\u09bf\u09ae\u09bf\u099f\u09c7\u09a1,\u09ac\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09ac\u09bf\u098f\u09b2) is a [[List of banks in Bangladesh#Specialized banks|state owned specialized commercial bank]] in [[Bangladesh]]. The bank came into effect with the merger of ailing [[Bangladesh Shilpa Bank Bhaban|Bangladesh Shilpa Bank]] and Shilpa Rin Sangstha, which were established in 1972 to provide loans and facilities to industrial units, help set up new industries and expand investment in Bangladesh.<ref name=\"ds\">{{cite news |title=Development Bank takes off |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/newDesign/news-details.php?nid=120388 |newspaper=The Daily Star |accessdate=4 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[File:BDBL Bhabhan.jpg|thumb|BDBL Bhaban, 8 Rajuk Avenue, Dhaka 1000,Head Office, [[Dhaka]].]]\n\n== History ==\nBangladesh Development Bank was established on 16 November 2009 as a Public Limited Company by merging the state owned Bangladesh Shilpa Bank and Bangladesh Shilpa Rin Sangstha, both which were established on 31 October 1972.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bdbl.com.bd/AboutUs_formation_BDBL.php|title=BDBL {{!}} Objectives|website=www.bdbl.com.bd|access-date=2019-08-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140907142513/http://bdbl.com.bd/AboutUs_formation_BDBL.php|archive-date=2014-09-07|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-116999|title=Bangladesh Development Bank starts journey Jan 3|date=2009-12-08|website=The Daily Star|language=en|access-date=2019-08-03}}</ref> Bangladesh Development Bank started in 2010 with 534 court cases concerning 21 billion taka and 24.6 billion taka in written off liabilities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-120388|title=Development Bank takes off|date=2010-01-04|website=The Daily Star|language=en|access-date=2019-08-03}}</ref>\n\nThe bank has had issues with loan defaulting, as of 2018, the total defaulted loans at the bank stood at 23.32 billion taka.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/opinion/no-frills/news/over-two-lakh-privileged-institutions-1635121|title=A loan defaulting epidemic: Over two lakh privileged institutions!|date=2018-09-18|website=The Daily Star|language=en|access-date=2019-08-03}}</ref> On 11 June 2019, the [[Anti-Corruption Commission (Bangladesh)|Anti-Corruption Commission]] sued for officials of the bank for allegedly  embezzling 250 million taka from the bank.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/city/news/4-bdbl-officials-used-embezzling-tk-25cr-1755547|title=4 BDBL officials sued for embezzling Tk 25cr|date=2019-06-11|website=The Daily Star|language=en|access-date=2019-08-03}}</ref>\n\n== Activities ==\nThe bank now offers a variety of services - Commercial Banking;SME Banking;Developmental Banking etc.\n\nForeign Exchange\n\u00b7 Local L/C\n\u00b7 Import L/C\n\u00b7 Export L/C\n\u00b7 Back to Back L/C\n\u00b7 Foreign remittance\n\u00b7 Foreign exchange buy & sale\nOther Banking Service:\n-Demand draft issue\n-Payment order issue\n-Selling of prize bond\n-Selling of saving certificate. [https://www.lawyersnjurists.com/article/overall-activities-of-bangladesh-development-bank-limited/]\n\n== Branches ==\nThere are currently 46 branches of BDBL banking across the country. The bank provides all kinds of commercial banking services to its customers through its 46 branch network in the country. The 46th branch of Bangladesh Development Bank Limited (BDBL) has been inaugurated at Tamalatla Bazar in Bagatipar, Natore.<ref name=\"new branch open\">{{cite news |title=Mohammad Mejbahuddin, Chairman of Bangladesh Development Bank Ltd, inaugurating the bank's 46th branch at Bagatipara in Natore recently. Bank's Managing Director Kazi Alamgir, General Manager Md Abdul Baki and Deputy Commissioner Mohammad Shah Riaz, among others, were present.|url=http://m.thedailynewnation.com/news/240759/mohammad-mejbahuddin-chairman-of-bangladesh-development-bank-ltd-inaugurating-the-banks-46th-branch-at-bagatipara-in-natore-recently-banks-managing-director-kazi-alamgir-general-manager-md-abdul-baki-and-deputy-commissioner-mohammad-shah-riaz-among-others-were-present |newspaper=thedailynewnation |accessdate=December 28, 2019}}</ref> Bangladesh Development Bank Limited (BDBL) operates online banking activities.BDBL SWIFT Code is BDDBBDDH\n\n== Technological Banking==\nCBS has begun on-line banking activities to control banking transactions as well as overall operations from the beginning of July 2015. Besides, all transactions are done through core banking software from any branch of BDBL, through Bangladesh Automated Check Clearing House (Batch). Inter-bank transactions of the kind are settled. Next is the inter-banking transaction across the country Under the Naden Bangladesh Electronic Funds Transfer Network (BEFTN) or 'Electronic Funds Transfer System', inter-bank electronic debit-credit transaction process is performed smoothly and fastest from any bank branch without any charges or fees at any time. Rapid and risk-free solutions using real time gross settlement (RTGS) From anywhere in the country amounts to one million or more to immediate payment. The fastest repayment of the inter-bank payment system is through RTGS. Customers and banks from anywhere in the world are able to make this transaction.\n\n== Management ==\nThe managing director controls the overall activities of the bank. The Managing Director is assisted by the General Manager and Department Heads working at the central office. Bank branch managers report the activities related to the matter directly to the managing director and to the department head. According to Article 95 of the Articles of Association of the Bank, there shall be a ten-member board of directors with the chairman as its chairman. The current chairman of the board of directors is former senior secretary Mohammad Mejbahuddin.<ref name=\"new chairmen joined in bdbl\">{{cite news |title=Chairman of Board of Directors of BDBL and former senior secretary Mohammad Mejbahuddin.|url=https://today.thefinancialexpress.com.bd/trade-market/chairman-of-board-of-directors-of-bdbl-and-former-senior-secretary-mohammad-mejbahuddin-1567358659?date=02-09-2019 |newspaper=the financial express | access-date=2019-09-02}} </ref>\n\n==Awards==\nBDBL also obtained Third Prize as the Best Corporate in the Banking Sector (State-owned Commercial Bank) given by The Institute of Cost and Management Accountants of Bangladesh (ICMAB) in its Best Corporate Award-2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=ICMAB Best Corporate Awards-2014|url=http://www.icmab.org.bd/event/best-corporate-awards-2014/|publisher=ICMAB|accessdate=20 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Strengths & Challenges==\nOUR STRENGTHS-\n*Good Corporate Governance & Practices.\n*Sound and strong capital & asset base.\n*Deep focus on quality control.\n*A dedicated line of human resource.\n*Culture of internal control and compliance. \n\nOur BUSINESS CHALLENGES-\n*Intense competition in the domestic market\n*Global economic slowdown\n*Strict capital requirement under Basel \u2013 III\n*Sharp fall in the interest rates on deposit\n*Increasing Business Risk. [http://www.bdbl.com.bd/image/Annual%20Report/BDBL_Annual%20Report_2015.pdf]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.bdbl.com.bd/ Bangladesh Development Bank Limited (BDBL) website]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n* \n{{Banks in Bangladesh}}\n\n[[Category:Banks of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Banks established in 2009]]\n\n\n{{Bangladesh-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Bangladesh Development Bank Limited\n| logo = Bangladesh_Development_Bank_Limited_LOGO.png\n| type = [[National bank|State owned bank]]\n| Extent of Shareholding = 100% share owned by the Government of Bangladesh\n| num_locations    = 46\n| key_people = {{Unbulleted list | Mohammad Mejbahuddin ([[Chairman]]) | kazi Alamgir([[Managing Director|MD]])}}\n| industry = [[International financial institutions|Development Bank]]<br />[[Bank]]<br />[[Capital Markets]] and allied industries\n| products = [[Retail banking]], [[Private banking]], [[Commercial bank|Corporate Banking]], [[Deposit (finance)|Deposits]], [[Mortgage loan]], Savings Scheme, Sanchay Scheme, Trade and Retail Forex\n| revenue = \n| net_income = \n| assets = {{BDTConvert|54.55|b|lk=yes}}\n| num_employees = About 775\n| foundation = [[Dhaka]], 16 November 2009\n| location = |\n| homepage = {{URL|www.bdbl.com.bd}}\n}}\n\n'''Bangladesh Development Bank''' (Bengali: \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09a1\u09c7\u09ad\u09c7\u09b2\u09aa\u09ae\u09c7\u09a8\u09cd\u099f \u09ac\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u0982\u0995 \u09b2\u09bf\u09ae\u09bf\u099f\u09c7\u09a1,\u09ac\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09ac\u09bf\u098f\u09b2) is a [[List of banks in Bangladesh#Specialized banks|state owned specialized commercial bank]] in [[Bangladesh]]. The bank came into effect with the merger of ailing [[Bangladesh Shilpa Bank Bhaban|Bangladesh Shilpa Bank]] and Shilpa Rin Sangstha, which were established in 1972 to provide loans and facilities to industrial units, help set up new industries and expand investment in Bangladesh.<ref name=\"ds\">{{cite news |title=Development Bank takes off |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/newDesign/news-details.php?nid=120388 |newspaper=The Daily Star |accessdate=4 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[File:BDBL Bhabhan.jpg|thumb|BDBL Bhaban, 8 Rajuk Avenue, Dhaka 1000,Head Office, [[Dhaka]].]]\n\n== History ==\nBangladesh Development Bank was established on 16 November 2009 as a Public Limited Company by merging the state owned Bangladesh Shilpa Bank and Bangladesh Shilpa Rin Sangstha, both which were established on 31 October 1972.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bdbl.com.bd/AboutUs_formation_BDBL.php|title=BDBL {{!}} Objectives|website=www.bdbl.com.bd|access-date=2019-08-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140907142513/http://bdbl.com.bd/AboutUs_formation_BDBL.php|archive-date=2014-09-07|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-116999|title=Bangladesh Development Bank starts journey Jan 3|date=2009-12-08|website=The Daily Star|language=en|access-date=2019-08-03}}</ref> Bangladesh Development Bank started in 2010 with 534 court cases concerning 21 billion taka and 24.6 billion taka in written off liabilities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-120388|title=Development Bank takes off|date=2010-01-04|website=The Daily Star|language=en|access-date=2019-08-03}}</ref>\n\nThe bank has had issues with loan defaulting, as of 2018, the total defaulted loans at the bank stood at 23.32 billion taka.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/opinion/no-frills/news/over-two-lakh-privileged-institutions-1635121|title=A loan defaulting epidemic: Over two lakh privileged institutions!|date=2018-09-18|website=The Daily Star|language=en|access-date=2019-08-03}}</ref> On 11 June 2019, the [[Anti-Corruption Commission (Bangladesh)|Anti-Corruption Commission]] sued for officials of the bank for allegedly  embezzling 250 million taka from the bank.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/city/news/4-bdbl-officials-used-embezzling-tk-25cr-1755547|title=4 BDBL officials sued for embezzling Tk 25cr|date=2019-06-11|website=The Daily Star|language=en|access-date=2019-08-03}}</ref>\n\n== Activities ==\nThe bank now offers a variety of services - Commercial Banking; SME Banking;Developmental Banking etc.\n\nForeign Exchange\n\u00b7 Local L/C\n\u00b7 Import L/C\n\u00b7 Export L/C\n\u00b7 Back to Back L/C\n\u00b7 Foreign remittance\n\u00b7 Foreign exchange buy & sale\n\nOther Banking Service:\n-Demand draft issue\n-Payment order issue\n-Selling of prize bond\n-Selling of saving certificate. [https://www.lawyersnjurists.com/article/overall-activities-of-bangladesh-development-bank-limited/]\n\n== Branches ==\nThere are currently 46 branches of BDBL banking across the country. The bank provides all kinds of commercial banking services to its customers through its 46 branch network in the country. The 46th branch of Bangladesh Development Bank Limited (BDBL) has been inaugurated at Tamalatla Bazar in Bagatipar, Natore.<ref name=\"new branch open\">{{cite news |title=Mohammad Mejbahuddin, Chairman of Bangladesh Development Bank Ltd, inaugurating the bank's 46th branch at Bagatipara in Natore recently. Bank's Managing Director Kazi Alamgir, General Manager Md Abdul Baki and Deputy Commissioner Mohammad Shah Riaz, among others, were present.|url=http://m.thedailynewnation.com/news/240759/mohammad-mejbahuddin-chairman-of-bangladesh-development-bank-ltd-inaugurating-the-banks-46th-branch-at-bagatipara-in-natore-recently-banks-managing-director-kazi-alamgir-general-manager-md-abdul-baki-and-deputy-commissioner-mohammad-shah-riaz-among-others-were-present |newspaper=thedailynewnation |accessdate=December 28, 2019}}</ref> Bangladesh Development Bank Limited (BDBL) operates online banking activities.BDBL SWIFT Code is BDDBBDDH\n\n== Technological Banking==\nCBS has begun on-line banking activities to control banking transactions as well as overall operations from the beginning of July 2015. Besides, all transactions are done through core banking software from any branch of BDBL, through Bangladesh Automated Check Clearing House (Batch). Inter-bank transactions of the kind are settled. Next is the inter-banking transaction across the country Under the Naden Bangladesh Electronic Funds Transfer Network (BEFTN) or 'Electronic Funds Transfer System', inter-bank electronic debit-credit transaction process is performed smoothly and fastest from any bank branch without any charges or fees at any time. Rapid and risk-free solutions using real time gross settlement (RTGS) From anywhere in the country amounts to one million or more to immediate payment. The fastest repayment of the inter-bank payment system is through RTGS. Customers and banks from anywhere in the world are able to make this transaction.\n\n== Management ==\nThe managing director controls the overall activities of the bank. The Managing Director is assisted by the General Manager and Department Heads working at the central office. Bank branch managers report the activities related to the matter directly to the managing director and to the department head. According to Article 95 of the Articles of Association of the Bank, there shall be a ten-member board of directors with the chairman as its chairman. The current chairman of the board of directors is former senior secretary Mohammad Mejbahuddin.<ref name=\"new chairmen joined in bdbl\">{{cite news |title=Chairman of Board of Directors of BDBL and former senior secretary Mohammad Mejbahuddin.|url=https://today.thefinancialexpress.com.bd/trade-market/chairman-of-board-of-directors-of-bdbl-and-former-senior-secretary-mohammad-mejbahuddin-1567358659?date=02-09-2019 |newspaper=the financial express | access-date=2019-09-02}} </ref>\n\n==Awards==\nBDBL also obtained Third Prize as the Best Corporate in the Banking Sector (State-owned Commercial Bank) given by The Institute of Cost and Management Accountants of Bangladesh (ICMAB) in its Best Corporate Award-2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=ICMAB Best Corporate Awards-2014|url=http://www.icmab.org.bd/event/best-corporate-awards-2014/|publisher=ICMAB|accessdate=20 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Strengths & Challenges==\nOUR STRENGTHS-\n*Good Corporate Governance & Practices.\n*Sound and strong capital & asset base.\n*Deep focus on quality control.\n*A dedicated line of human resource.\n*Culture of internal control and compliance. \n\nOur BUSINESS CHALLENGES-\n*Intense competition in the domestic market\n*Global economic slowdown\n*Strict capital requirement under Basel \u2013 III\n*Sharp fall in the interest rates on deposit\n*Increasing Business Risk. [http://www.bdbl.com.bd/image/Annual%20Report/BDBL_Annual%20Report_2015.pdf]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.bdbl.com.bd/ Bangladesh Development Bank Limited (BDBL) website]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n* \n{{Banks in Bangladesh}}\n\n[[Category:Banks of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Banks established in 2009]]\n\n\n{{Bangladesh-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Engr. Md. Nadimul Islam", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eActivities", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bangladesh_Development_Bank"}
{"title_page": "Banana chip", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Banana chips|the song by Shonen Knife|Happy Hour (Shonen Knife album)}}\n{{Infobox nutritional value\n| name            = Banana chips\n| image           = Banana Chip BNC.jpg\n| image_alt       = Dried banana chips\n| caption         = Dried banana chips\n| serving_size    = 100g\n| kJ              = 2170\n| water           = 4.3 g\n| carbs           = 58.40g\n| sugars          = 35.34g\n| fiber           = 7.7g\n| fat             = 33.60g\n| satfat          = 28.970g\n| monofat         = 1.950g\n| polyfat         = 0.630g\n| protein         = 2.30g\n| vitA_ug         = 4\n| vitA_iu         = 83\n| thiamin_mg      = 0.085\n| riboflavin_mg   = 0.017\n| niacin_mg       = 0.710\t\n| vitB6_mg        = 0.260\n| folate_ug       = 14\n| vitC_mg         = 6.3\t\n| vitE_mg         = 0.24\t\n| vitK_ug         = 1.3\t\n| calcium_mg      = 18\n| iron_mg         = 1.25\n| magnesium_mg    = 76\n| phosphorus_mg   = 56\n| potassium_mg    = 536\n| sodium_mg       = 6\n| zinc_mg         = 0.75\n| copper_mg       = 0.205\n| source_usda     = 1\n| note=[https://ndb.nal.usda.gov/ndb/foods/show/19400?fgcd=&manu=&format=Abridged&count=&max=25&offset=&sort=default&order=asc&qlookup=BANANA+chip&ds=&qt=&qp=&qa=&qn=&q=&ing= Link to USDA Database entry]\n}}\n\n'''Banana chips''' originated in India are dried, generally crispy slices of [[banana]]s (fruits of [[herbaceous plant]]s of the [[genus]] ''[[Musa (genus)|Musa]]'' of the soft, sweet \"dessert banana\" variety). They can be covered with [[sugar]] or [[honey]] and have a sweet taste, or are more commonly fried in oil and spices and have a salty or spicy taste.<ref>{{cite web|last=Food processing|first=EPa|title=How to Make Sweet and Salted Banana Chips|url=http://www.mixph.com/2006/09/how-to-make-sweet-and-salted-banana-chips.html|accessdate=16 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111228190442/http://www.mixph.com/2006/09/how-to-make-sweet-and-salted-banana-chips.html|archive-date=28 December 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> \n[[File:Jaggery Chips BNC.jpg|thumb|Jaggery chips]] Banana chips are similar to [[chifle]], usually made from firmer, starchier fruit varieties of the genus ''Musa'' commercially called [[Plantain (cooking)|plantain]]s or \"cooking bananas\".\n\n==Fried==\n[[File:Banana Chips preparation.jpg|thumb|Banana chips being prepared by [[deep frying]]]]\nFried banana chips are usually produced from under-ripe banana slices [[deep frying|deep-fried]] in [[sunflower oil]] or [[coconut oil]]. These chips are dry (like potato chips), contain about 4% water (table), and can be salted, spiced, sugar coated or jaggery coated. Sometimes [[Isoamyl acetate|banana flavoring]] is added. If ripe bananas are used, they come out oily. They are used for desserts, not for dry chips.\n\n==Dried==\nSome varieties of banana chips can be produced using only [[food dehydration]]. Banana slices that are only dehydrated are not dark yellow and crunchy, but rather are brown, leathery and chewy. They are very sweet and have an intense banana flavor. These are ideally made from bananas that are fully ripe. Another kind is made by baking in an oven, although this process may not result in the same intense banana flavor.\n\n==Nutrition==\nFried banana chips are 4% water, 58% [[carbohydrate]]s, 34% [[fat]], and 2% [[protein]]. In a 100 gram reference amount, fried banana chips supply 520 [[calorie]]s and are a rich source (20% or more the [[Daily Value]], DV) of [[magnesium]] (21% DV) and [[vitamin B6]] (20% DV), with moderate amounts of [[iron]], [[copper]], and [[potassium]] (10% to 11% DV) (table). Other [[micronutrient]]s are in negligible amounts.\n\n==Uses and variations==\n\n===India===\n\n[[Fried plantain]] chips, known as ''nenthra-kaaya oopperi'' or ''upperi'' in [[Kerala]], are fried in [[coconut oil]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/magazine/the-taste-of-kerala/article4605855.ece |title=Banana Chips from Kerala, india|publisher=The Hindu |date= |accessdate=2013-04-13}}</ref> Both ripe and unripe plantains are used for this type of chip preparation. The chips may be coated with [[spice mix|masala]] or [[jaggery]] to form spicy and sweet variations. Plain banana and plantain chips are called ''pachkkaya varuthathu'' and ''kaya upperi'', respectively; sweet jaggery-banana chips are called ''sharkara upperi''. It is an integral part of the traditional Kerala meal called [[sadya]] served during weddings and festivals, such as [[Onam]].\n\n===Indonesia===\n\nBanana is a native plant of [[Maritime Southeast Asia]] and the people of the archipelago has developed many uses of it for ages, including as a snack. In [[Indonesian cuisine|Indonesia]], banana chip is called ''kripik pisang'', and is considered as a variant of crispy ''[[kripik]]'' (traditional chip or crisp). ''Kripik pisang'' is a popular crispy snack and can be commonly found in Indonesia, although it seems to be more prevalent in Java and Sumatra. \n\nUsually unripe green bananas are thinly sliced, soaked in lime and salt water solution, and being deep fried as chips.<ref>{{cite web | title = banana chips (keripik pisang) | work = Indonesian original recipe | url = http://indonesiaoriginalrecipes.blogspot.co.id/2013/11/banana-chips-keripik-pisang.html}}</ref> Unripe banana is well suited for [[deep frying]] due to its low content of water and sugar, while having high starch content. ''[[Pisang goreng]]'' is another fried banana snack, although it is not thinly sliced and serves as a sweet hot snack.\n\n===America===\nThe chips are often part of [[muesli]] and [[nut (fruit)|nut]] mixes. Other chips, such as [[patacones]], are [[salt]]y.\nSimilar chips called [[chifle]] are made from [[Plantain (cooking)|plantain]]s, the family of fruit that bananas come from. In tropical American cultures, all bananas are considered plantains, but not all plantains are bananas. These deep-fried plantain chips are also quite popular in the southeastern part of Mexico, especially in the state of [[Tabasco]].\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Chips Palakkad.jpg|Fried banana chips\nFile:Keripik pisang Lampung.JPG|Indonesian ''[[kripik]] pisang'' (banana chips)\nFile:Homemade_4_Cut_Banana_Chips.jpg|Homemade Banana Chips\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n\n{{portal|Food}}\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Apple chips]]\n* [[Banana]] - In popular culture and commerce, \"banana\" usually refers to soft, sweet \"dessert\" ''Musa'' cultivars.\n* [[Banana powder]]\n* [[Chifle]] - a similar salty snack chip made from plantains.\n* [[Plantain (cooking)|Plantain]] - ''Musa'' cultivars with firmer, starchier fruit\n* [[Tostones]] - a similar salty snack made from plantains.\n* ''[[Kripik]]'' - Indonesian chips, ''kripik pisang'' is Indonesian banana chips\n* [[List of deep fried foods]]\n* [[List of dried foods]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{commons}}\n\n{{Banana}}\n{{Chips and crisps}}\n{{Deep frying foods}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Banana Chips}}\n[[Category:Snack foods]]\n[[Category:Dried fruit]]\n[[Category:Banana dishes]]\n[[Category:Deep fried foods]]\n[[Category:Indian snack foods]]\n[[Category:Indonesian snack foods]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Banana chips|the song by Shonen Knife|Happy Hour (Shonen Knife album)}}\n{{Infobox nutritional value\n| name            = Banana chips\n| image           = Banana Chip BNC.jpg\n| image_alt       = Dried banana chips\n| caption         = Dried banana chips\n| serving_size    = 100g\n| kJ              = 2170\n| water           = 4.3 g\n| carbs           = 58.40g\n| sugars          = 35.34g\n| fiber           = 7.7g\n| fat             = 33.60g\n| satfat          = 28.970g\n| monofat         = 1.950g\n| polyfat         = 0.630g\n| protein         = 2.30g\n| vitA_ug         = 4\n| vitA_iu         = 83\n| thiamin_mg      = 0.085\n| riboflavin_mg   = 0.017\n| niacin_mg       = 0.710\t\n| vitB6_mg        = 0.260\n| folate_ug       = 14\n| vitC_mg         = 6.3\t\n| vitE_mg         = 0.24\t\n| vitK_ug         = 1.3\t\n| calcium_mg      = 18\n| iron_mg         = 1.25\n| magnesium_mg    = 76\n| phosphorus_mg   = 56\n| potassium_mg    = 536\n| sodium_mg       = 6\n| zinc_mg         = 0.75\n| copper_mg       = 0.205\n| source_usda     = 1\n| note=[https://ndb.nal.usda.gov/ndb/foods/show/19400?fgcd=&manu=&format=Abridged&count=&max=25&offset=&sort=default&order=asc&qlookup=BANANA+chip&ds=&qt=&qp=&qa=&qn=&q=&ing= Link to USDA Database entry]\n}}\n\n'''Banana chips''' orginated in India are dried, generally crispy slices of [[banana]]s (fruits of [[herbaceous plant]]s of the [[genus]] ''[[Musa (genus)|Musa]]'' of the soft, sweet \"dessert banana\" variety). They can be covered with [[sugar]] or [[honey]] and have a sweet taste, or are more commonly fried in oil and spices and have a salty or spicy taste.<ref>{{cite web|last=Food processing|first=EPa|title=How to Make Sweet and Salted Banana Chips|url=http://www.mixph.com/2006/09/how-to-make-sweet-and-salted-banana-chips.html|accessdate=16 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111228190442/http://www.mixph.com/2006/09/how-to-make-sweet-and-salted-banana-chips.html|archive-date=28 December 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> \n[[File:Jaggery Chips BNC.jpg|thumb|Jaggery chips]] Banana chips are similar to [[chifle]], usually made from firmer, starchier fruit varieties of the genus ''Musa'' commercially called [[Plantain (cooking)|plantain]]s or \"cooking bananas\".\n\n==Fried==\n[[File:Banana Chips preparation.jpg|thumb|Banana chips being prepared by [[deep frying]]]]\nFried banana chips are usually produced from under-ripe banana slices [[deep frying|deep-fried]] in [[sunflower oil]] or [[coconut oil]]. These chips are dry (like potato chips), contain about 4% water (table), and can be salted, spiced, sugar coated or jaggery coated. Sometimes [[Isoamyl acetate|banana flavoring]] is added. If ripe bananas are used, they come out oily. They are used for desserts, not for dry chips.\n\n==Dried==\nSome varieties of banana chips can be produced using only [[food dehydration]]. Banana slices that are only dehydrated are not dark yellow and crunchy, but rather are brown, leathery and chewy. They are very sweet and have an intense banana flavor. These are ideally made from bananas that are fully ripe. Another kind is made by baking in an oven, although this process may not result in the same intense banana flavor.\n\n==Nutrition==\nFried banana chips are 4% water, 58% [[carbohydrate]]s, 34% [[fat]], and 2% [[protein]]. In a 100 gram reference amount, fried banana chips supply 520 [[calorie]]s and are a rich source (20% or more the [[Daily Value]], DV) of [[magnesium]] (21% DV) and [[vitamin B6]] (20% DV), with moderate amounts of [[iron]], [[copper]], and [[potassium]] (10% to 11% DV) (table). Other [[micronutrient]]s are in negligible amounts.\n\n==Uses and variations==\n\n===India===\n\n[[Fried plantain]] chips, known as ''nenthra-kaaya oopperi'' or ''upperi'' in [[Kerala]], are fried in [[coconut oil]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/magazine/the-taste-of-kerala/article4605855.ece |title=Banana Chips from Kerala, india|publisher=The Hindu |date= |accessdate=2013-04-13}}</ref> Both ripe and unripe plantains are used for this type of chip preparation. The chips may be coated with [[spice mix|masala]] or [[jaggery]] to form spicy and sweet variations. Plain banana and plantain chips are called ''pachkkaya varuthathu'' and ''kaya upperi'', respectively; sweet jaggery-banana chips are called ''sharkara upperi''. It is an integral part of the traditional Kerala meal called [[sadya]] served during weddings and festivals, such as [[Onam]].\n\n===Indonesia===\n\nBanana is a native plant of [[Maritime Southeast Asia]] and the people of the archipelago has developed many uses of it for ages, including as a snack. In [[Indonesian cuisine|Indonesia]], banana chip is called ''kripik pisang'', and is considered as a variant of crispy ''[[kripik]]'' (traditional chip or crisp). ''Kripik pisang'' is a popular crispy snack and can be commonly found in Indonesia, although it seems to be more prevalent in Java and Sumatra. \n\nUsually unripe green bananas are thinly sliced, soaked in lime and salt water solution, and being deep fried as chips.<ref>{{cite web | title = banana chips (keripik pisang) | work = Indonesian original recipe | url = http://indonesiaoriginalrecipes.blogspot.co.id/2013/11/banana-chips-keripik-pisang.html}}</ref> Unripe banana is well suited for [[deep frying]] due to its low content of water and sugar, while having high starch content. ''[[Pisang goreng]]'' is another fried banana snack, although it is not thinly sliced and serves as a sweet hot snack.\n\n===America===\nThe chips are often part of [[muesli]] and [[nut (fruit)|nut]] mixes. Other chips, such as [[patacones]], are [[salt]]y.\nSimilar chips called [[chifle]] are made from [[Plantain (cooking)|plantain]]s, the family of fruit that bananas come from. In tropical American cultures, all bananas are considered plantains, but not all plantains are bananas. These deep-fried plantain chips are also quite popular in the southeastern part of Mexico, especially in the state of [[Tabasco]].\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Chips Palakkad.jpg|Fried banana chips\nFile:Keripik pisang Lampung.JPG|Indonesian ''[[kripik]] pisang'' (banana chips)\nFile:Homemade_4_Cut_Banana_Chips.jpg|Homemade Banana Chips\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n\n{{portal|Food}}\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Apple chips]]\n* [[Banana]] - In popular culture and commerce, \"banana\" usually refers to soft, sweet \"dessert\" ''Musa'' cultivars.\n* [[Banana powder]]\n* [[Chifle]] - a similar salty snack chip made from plantains.\n* [[Plantain (cooking)|Plantain]] - ''Musa'' cultivars with firmer, starchier fruit\n* [[Tostones]] - a similar salty snack made from plantains.\n* ''[[Kripik]]'' - Indonesian chips, ''kripik pisang'' is Indonesian banana chips\n* [[List of deep fried foods]]\n* [[List of dried foods]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{commons}}\n\n{{Banana}}\n{{Chips and crisps}}\n{{Deep frying foods}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Banana Chips}}\n[[Category:Snack foods]]\n[[Category:Dried fruit]]\n[[Category:Banana dishes]]\n[[Category:Deep fried foods]]\n[[Category:Indian snack foods]]\n[[Category:Indonesian snack foods]]\n", "name_user": "Neils51", "label": "safe", "comment": "sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Banana_chip"}
{"title_page": "Ogden, Utah", "text_new": "{{short description|City in Utah, United States}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!--See Template:Infobox Settlement for additional fields that may be available-->\n<!--See the Table at Infobox Settlement for all fields and descriptions of usage-->\n<!-- Basic info  ---------------->| currency = dollar($)\n| official_name                   = Ogden, Utah\n| native_name                     = <!-- for cities whose native name is not in English -->\n| nickname                        = Junction City\n| settlement_type                 = [[City]]\n| motto                           = Still Untamed\n<!-- images and maps  ----------->\n| image_skyline                   = US Utah Ogden Montage.jpg\n| imagesize                       = \n| image_caption                   = From top left to bottom right: Ogden High School, Weber State University Bell Tower, Peery's Egyptian Theater, Downtown, Gantry Sign, aerial view\n| image_flag                      = \n| flag_size                       = \n| image_seal                      = \n| seal_size                       = \n| image_shield                    = \n| shield_size                     = \n| image_blank_emblem              = \n| blank_emblem_type               = \n| blank_emblem_size               = \n| image_map                       = Weber County Utah incorporated and unincorporated areas Ogden highlighted.svg\n| mapsize                         = 260px\n| map_caption                     = Location in [[Weber County, UT|Weber County]] and the state of [[Utah]]\n<!-- Location ------------------>\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = [[United States]]\n| subdivision_type1               = [[U.S. state|State]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Utah]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of counties in Utah|County]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Weber County, Utah|Weber]]\n| subdivision_type3               = \n| subdivision_name3   