{"title_page": "Rolf Henrich", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Rolf Henrich\n| image = \n| caption = \n| image_size = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date  = {{b-da|24 February 1944}}\n| birth_place = [[Magdeburg]], Saxony-Anhalt, [[Nazi Germany|Germany]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| party       = [[Socialist Unity Party of Germany|SED]] (1964)<br />[[New Forum|NF]] (1989)<br />[[Social Democratic Party of Germany|SPD]] (1990)\n| religion    = \n| occupation =  Writer<br />lawyer<br />politician\n| parents = \n| spouse = Heidelore\n| children = Falk\n| website  =\n}}\n\n'''Rolf Henrich''' (born [[Magdeburg]] 24 February 1944) is a writer and lawyer.<ref name=LeMORH1>{{cite web|url=http://www.hdg.de/lemo/biografie/rolf-henrich|title=Rolf Henrich geb. 1944|publisher=Stiftung Haus der Geschichte der Bundesrepublik Deutschland, [[Bonn]]|date=4 December 2014|author=|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref> In September 1989 he became a co-founder and leading member of the [[New Forum]] movement.<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenRH>{{cite web|url=http://www.bundesstiftung-aufarbeitung.de/wer-war-wer-in-der-ddr-%2363%3B-1424.html?ID=1348|author1= [[Helmut M\u00fcller-Enbergs]] |author2= Jan Wielgohs|title = Henrich, Rolf * 24.2.1944 Dissident|publisher= Bundesstiftung zur Aufarbeitung der SED-Diktatur: Biographische Datenbanken |accessdate= 27 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nHis book \"The Custodial State. On the Failure of Real-life Socialism\" (''\"Der vormundschaftliche Staat. Vom Versagen des real existierenden Sozialismus\"'')<ref name=DieVorStaRH>{{cite book |title=Der vormundschaftliche Staat: Vom Versagen des real existierenden Sozialismus|author=Rolf Henrich|publisher=[[Rowohlt Verlag#rororo Taschenb\u00fccher|Rowohlt Taschenbuch Verlag]]|date=1989|isbn= 978-3499125362}}</ref> had appeared in April 1989 and was a powerful stimulus along the route to the [[:de:B\u00fcrgerbewegung|Citizens' Movement]] that within a couple of years had led to [[Die Wende|the end]] of the [[German Democratic Republic]] as a standalone state.<ref name=rev89RH>{{cite web |url=http://revolution89.de/?PID=static,Zeitzeugen,00220-Henrich,Index_en |title=Rolf Henrich|author=[[Ilko-Sascha Kowalczuk]]|publisher=[[:de:Robert-Havemann-Gesellschaft|Robert-Havemann-Gesellschaft e.V.]], Berlin|date=|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Life ==\n\n===Early years===\nHenrich was born in [[Magdeburg]], roughly equidistant between [[Hanover]] and [[Berlin]], and on the eastern side of the [[Inner German border|border]] that divided [[East Germany]] from [[West Germany]]. After [[Abitur|successfully completing]] his school career he went on to study Law at the [[Humboldt University of Berlin|Humboldt University]] in Berlin. At the age of 20 he joined the country's ruling [[Socialist Unity Party of Germany|SED (party)]]<ref name=rev89RH/> and three years later he became an [[Informal collaborators (East Germany)|Informal collaborator (IM / ''Informeller Mitarbeiter'')]] for the [[Stasi|Ministry for State Security (Stasi)]].<ref name=rev89RH/> Between 1964 and 1969 he is listed as an IM in the Stasi files under the code name \"IM Streit\".<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenRH/>\n\n===The student===\nTwenty years later he would describe himself at age 20 as having joined the [[Socialist Unity Party of Germany|SED]] \"out of conviction\": \"Back then\", he later recalled, he was \"even a bit fanatical\"<ref name=spiegel131989/><ref>\"[ich war]...begeisterter [[Free German Youth|FDJler]]...Ich war damals sogar ein bi\u00dfchen fanatisch.</ref> A powerful adumbration of future disenchantment with the East German regime nevertheless came in 1968, in the context of student discussions of the [[Prague Spring]]<ref name=BerKurRH>{{cite web |url=http://www.berliner-kurier.de/kiez-stadt/meine-wende--rolf-henrich--stell-dich-auf--die-seite-derer--auf-die-alle-mit--dem-finger-zeigen-,7169128,28347830,item,0.html|title=Meine Wende: Rolf Henrich \"Stell dich auf die Seite derer, auf die alle mit dem Finger zeigen\"|author=Gundula Mieke|publisher=[[Berliner Kurier]]|date=8 September 2014|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref> when he was officially reprimanded for \"revisionism\" and \"psychologizing the law\",<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenRH/> and suffered the withdrawal of a previously agreed research scholarship.<ref name=LeMORH>{{cite web |url=http://hdg.de/lemo/html/biografien/HenrichRolf/index.html|title= Rolf Henrich: Jurist|publisher=Stiftung Haus der Geschichte der Bundesrepublik Deutschland , [[Bonn]]|author=|date=|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref> He was also required to change the subject of his dissertation, now addressing the subject \"The next tasks of Soviet power\" (''\"Die n\u00e4chsten Aufgaben der Sowjetmacht\"''): he nevertheless accomplished his own task, receiving his degree-diploma with a top grade.<ref name=spiegel131989/>\n\n===The young lawyer===\nAfter receiving his Law degree Henrich went on to perform his [[Military service]] in the [[National People's Army]] before taking a post as a research assistant at the prestigious [[:de:Deutsche Akademie f\u00fcr Staats- und Rechtswissenschaft|\"Walter Ulbricht\" German Legal Academy]] (as it was known at the time) in the [[Babelsberg]] quarter of [[Potsdam]].<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenRH/> In 1973 he set himself up as a lawyer in [[Eisenh\u00fcttenstadt]].  Here he supported [[Socialist Unity Party of Germany|The Party]] within the local \"Collective of Lawyers\" (''\"Kollegium der Rechtsanw\u00e4lte\"'') as [[Socialist Unity Party of Germany#Party Secretaries|Party Secretary]].<ref name=BerZeiRH01>{{cite web |url=http://www.berliner-zeitung.de/archiv/der-regimekritiker-und-anwalt-rolf-henrich-ueber-den-niedergang-des-sed-regimes-und-die-frage--warum-die-ddr-kein-rechtsstaat-war-der-despot-war-nur-noch-ein-phantom,10810590,10678382.html|title=Der Despot war nur noch ein Phantom: Der Regimekritiker und Anwalt Rolf Henrich \u00fcber den Niedergang des SED-Regimes und die Frage, warum die DDR kein Rechtsstaat war|publisher= [[Berliner Zeitung]] (online)|author=[[:de:Adelbert Reif|Adelbert Reif]]|date=9 November 2009|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref> During this period he also undertook further studies, almost certainly of a political nature, at the regional party academy in [[Frankfurt (Oder)|Frankfurt (on the River Oder)]].<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenRH/>\n\n===Growing disenchantment===\nThe arrest of [[Rudolf Bahro]] in 1977 affected Henrich deeply<ref name=ZeitRH>{{cite web | url=http://www.zeit.de/1989/15/anders-als-bahro|title=Anders als Bahro: Ein Buch brachte dem DDR-Anwalt Rolf Henrich Berufsverbot ein |author= [[:de:Marlies Menge|Marlies Menge]]|publisher= [[Die Zeit]] (online)|date= 7 April 1989|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref> and he slowly became increasingly disillusioned with the East German regime and its Soviet-style Socialism,<ref name=LeMORH/> composing several highly critical essays (which remained unpublished).<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenRH/> He would later recall his disenchantment, which had set in and then developed ever since he started to practice in [[Eisenh\u00fcttenstadt]], with the way the law was applied in the [[German Democratic Republic]].<ref name=spiegel131989/> Nevertheless, Rolf Henrich remained a relatively discrete dissident through the early 1980s. He himself later spoke of the need he had experienced slowly to free himself from the old dogmatism as a laborious process of internal conflict.<ref name=spiegel131989/><ref>\"Ich mu\u00dfte mich erst langsam aus dem Dogmatismus befreien, das war ein m\u00fchsamer Proze\u00df innerer Auseinandersetzung.\"</ref> He did, however, attract the interest of the [[Stasi|Ministry for State Security]] whose principal office in [[Eisenh\u00fcttenstadt]] was in the Bergstra\u00dfe (\"Mountain Street\"), close to his own office.<ref name=spiegel131989/> For approximately two years, starting in 1987, the camera installed to monitor people entering and leaving the Ministry was positioned so that it could periodically swing round and point directly at Henrich's desk, through his office window across the road.<ref name=spiegel131989>{{ cite web |url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-13495376.html |title=Die Wahrheit \u00f6ffentlich machen Ein fr\u00fcherer Parteisekret\u00e4r rechnet mit dem SED-System ab Der SED steht, rechtzeitig zur 40-Jahr-Feier der DDR, ein neuer Dissident ins Haus. Elf Jahre nach Bahro klagt ein Genosse die Parteif\u00fchrung \u00f6ffentlich an, sie halte sich nur mit Hilfe eines brutalen und allgegenw\u00e4rtigen Polizeiapparates an der Macht, die Stasi sei \"der Garant der Sozialversicherung\" f\u00fcr die Gerontokraten im Politb\u00fcro|publisher=[[Der Spiegel]] (online)|date=27 March 1989|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Into the limelight===\nHenrich's public profile was greatly raised with the publication in April 1989 of his book \"The Custodial State. On the Failure of Real-life Socialism\" (''\"Der vormundschaftliche Staat. Vom Versagen des real existierenden Sozialismus\"'')<ref name=DieVorStaRH/> There was at this time no question of anything so critical of the regime being published in [[East Germany]]: the book was published in [[West Germany]]<ref name=LeMORH/> where it received wide coverage in the broadcast and print media.<ref name=spiegel131989/> The book's publication evidently came as a surprise to the authorities.<ref name=rev89RH/> It presented a devastating and detailed criticism of a state where socialism had not progressed beyond the \"larval stage\" (''\"Sozialismus im Larvenstadium\"'') and the [[Stasi|security services]] felt free to operate outside the law.<ref name=spiegel131989/> In some ways it was a conscious follow-up to \"The Alternative\",<ref name=spiegel351977>{{cite web|title=Das trifft den Parteiapparat ins Herz. Ein SED-Funktion\u00e4r kritisiert den DDR-Sozialismus|language=German|trans-title=That's gonna hit the heart of the party. An SED functionary criticises GDR socialism.|date=22 August 1977|accessdate=27 January 2015|publisher=[[Der Spiegel]] (online)|url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-40763980.html}}</ref> the publication of which in 1977 had led to [[Rudolf Bahro|its author's]] arrest and subsequent deportation, but twelve years on Rolf Heinrich was much more analytically pessimistic about the way ahead for Socialism in the German Democratic Republic than Rudolf Bahro had been.<ref name=spiegel131989/> In East Germany Henrich was expelled from the ruling SED (party) and excluded from the \"Collective of Lawyers\" (''\"Kollegium der Rechtsanw\u00e4lte\"'')<ref name=BerKurRH/> which effectively terminated, for the time being, his legal career in [[Eisenh\u00fcttenstadt]]. The widespread assumption was that Rolf Henrich, like Bahro, would now be arrested and then deported or \"[[:de:H\u00e4ftlingsfreikauf|sold]]\" to [[West Germany|the west]].<ref name=spiegel131989/> That did not happen this time, however, possibly because behind the scenes the East Germany leadership hardliners were themselves struggling with a loss of self-confidence resulting from the [[Perestroika|political loosening]] now under way in the [[Soviet Union]] itself.<ref name=spiegelperestroika>{{ cite web |url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/ende-der-ddr-gorbatschow-war-an-stasi-uebernahme-durch-kgb-interessiert-a-654408.html|title= Ende der DDR: Gorbatschow war an Stasi-\u00dcbernahme durch KGB interessiert: Skurriles vom Untergang der DDR: Nach SPIEGEL-Informationen wollte Michail Gorbatschow im Jahr 1990, dass der KGB die Auslandsspionage der Stasi und das gesamte IM-Netz \u00fcbernimmt. Die sowjetische Bestandsgarantie f\u00fcr die DDR hat der damalige Kreml-Chef schon vor dem Untergang des Landes widerrufen.|publisher=[[Der Spiegel]] (online)|author=|date=10 October 2009|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref> Another explanation is that the regime was aware of the scale of the publicity Heinrich's book had already received both within and outside the German Democratic Republic and did not arrest him \"for political reasons\".<ref name=rev89RH/>\n\n===New Forum===\nEarly in September 1989, at [[Gr\u00fcnheide (Mark)|Gr\u00fcnheide]], Rolf Henrich was one of the 30 signatories of the founding proclamation that gave birth to the [[New Forum]] movement. By the end of 1989 more than 200,000 had signed the proclamation despite New Forum having been identified by the East German [[Socialist Unity Party of Germany|governing party]] as illegal. By this time, in any event, [[Die Wende|the Berlin wall]] had been breached by demonstrators on the eastern side early in November 1989, and when it became clear that the [[Group of Soviet Forces in Germany|fraternal Soviet troops]] had no instructions to prevent people from crossing it, the gate was seen to have been left open for a [[German reunification|reunification]] process that now appeared unstoppable.\n{{Quote box|align=right|width=40%|\n:::'''Rolf Henrich: Published Works'''\n* ''Der vormundschaftliche Staat. Vom Versagen des real existierenden Sozialismus.'' Rowohlt Verlag Hamburg 1989, {{ISBN|3-499-12536-6}}\n* ''Gewalt und Form in einer vulkanischen Welt, Aufs\u00e4tze 1991\u201396.'' Berlin 1996, {{ISBN|3-932458-01-X}}\n* ''Die Schlinge.'' Eichborn Verlag Frankfurt/Main 2001, {{ISBN|3-8218-0707-5}} (his first novel)\n}}\nAs part of that process, between December 1989 and March 1990 a [[:de:Runder Tisch|Round Table forum]] was convened to work through the practical steps needed for German reunification. Rolf Henrich participated in the Round Table discussions on behalf of [[New Forum]].<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenRH/> Henrich set himself two principal tasks within the process. The hated [[Stasi|Ministry for State Security]] had to be abolished. There had been some suggestion that the institution might be reconfigured as a new \"National Security Agency\" (''\"Amt f\u00fcr Nationale Sicherheit\"''). For Henrich, that would have been a mere re-labeling and as such totally unacceptable.<ref name=BerKurRH/> His second task was to help draft and enact a new election law for [[East Germany]], and to set a date for a democratically configured election to take place.<ref name=BerKurRH/> On 18 March 1990 the first, and as matters turned out, last, free [[1990 East German general election|parliamentary election]] in the history of the [[German Democratic Republic]] was held. After this Rolf Henrich was satisfied that his own contribution to the Round Table exercise had been successfully completed.<ref name=BerKurRH/> In November 1989 the de facto ban that seven months earlier had prevented him from working as a lawyer had been revoked and he was by now free to return to work at his lawyer's office in [[Eisenh\u00fcttenstadt]].<ref name=LeMORH/>\n\n===Career options===\nHenrich later told an interviewer that [[Manfred Gerlach]], who had been the East German head of state between 3 December 1989 and 18 March 1990, had offered him a job as President of the [[Supreme Court of East Germany|country's Supreme Court]], but Henrich turned down that job along with an invitation to take a government post as secretary of state in the Ministry of Justice. Henrich evidently thought he might have independence issues or become a \"figleaf\" with a high-profile post in the East German judicial-political establishment. To maximize legitimacy, such jobs should go to an \"outsider\".<ref name=BerKurRH/>\n\nThere had also been a project involving the [[Gruner + Jahr]] publishing conglomerate to set up a pan-regional daily newspaper called \"Die Ostdeutsche\", based on the model of the highly successful [[S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung]]. That project failed because the newspaper market turned out to be overcrowded already.<ref name=BerKurRH/>\n\n[[German reunification]] formally took place in October 1990 and Rolf Henrich returned to his life as a provincial lawyer in [[Eisenh\u00fcttenstadt]]. His public profile never entirely vanished, however: he continued to give occasional press interviews and to publish the occasional book. In the courts he has worked as a defense lawyer in controversial cases including those involving former East German border guards charged in connection with shootings at the [[Berlin Wall]].<ref name=rev89RH/>\n\n==Awards and honours==\n* 2000 [[:de:Deutscher Nationalpreis|German National prize]] of the [[:de:Deutsche Nationalstiftung|German National Foundation]]<ref name=LeMORH/> (joint winner)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Henrich, Rolf}}\n[[Category:German lawyers]]\n[[Category:East German dissidents]]\n[[Category:Socialist Unity Party of Germany members]]\n[[Category:New Forum (East Germany) members]]\n[[Category:Social Democratic Party of Germany politicians]]\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:German male writers]]\n[[Category:People of the Stasi]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Rolf Henrich\n| image = \n| caption = \n| image_size = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date  = {{b-da|24 February 1944}}\n| birth_place = [[Magdeburg]], Saxony-Anhalt, [[Nazi Germany|Germany]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| party         = [[Socialist Unity Party of Germany|SED]] (1964)<br />[[New Forum|NF]] (1989)<br />[[Social Democratic Party of Germany|SPD]] (1990)\n| religion         = \n| occupation =  Writer<br />lawyer<br />politician\n| parents = \n| spouse = Heidelore\n| children = Falk\n| website  =  \n}}\n\n'''Rolf Henrich''' (born [[Magdeburg]] 24 February 1944) is a writer and lawyer.<ref name=LeMORH>{{cite web|url=http://www.hdg.de/lemo/biografie/rolf-henrich|title=Rolf Henrich geb. 1944|publisher=Stiftung Haus der Geschichte der Bundesrepublik Deutschland, [[Bonn]]|date=4 December 2014|author=|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref> In September 1989 he became a co-founder and leading member of the [[New Forum]] movement.<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenRH>{{cite web|url=http://www.bundesstiftung-aufarbeitung.de/wer-war-wer-in-der-ddr-%2363%3B-1424.html?ID=1348|author1= [[Helmut M\u00fcller-Enbergs]] |author2= Jan Wielgohs|title = Henrich, Rolf * 24.2.1944 Dissident|publisher= Bundesstiftung zur Aufarbeitung der SED-Diktatur: Biographische Datenbanken |accessdate= 27 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nHis book \"The Custodial State. On the Failure of Real-life Socialism\" (''\"Der vormundschaftliche Staat. Vom Versagen des real existierenden Sozialismus\"'')<ref name=DieVorStaRH>{{cite book |title=Der vormundschaftliche Staat: Vom Versagen des real existierenden Sozialismus|author=Rolf Henrich|publisher=[[Rowohlt Verlag#rororo Taschenb\u00fccher|Rowohlt Taschenbuch Verlag]]|date=1989|isbn= 978-3499125362}}</ref> had appeared in April 1989 and was a powerful stimulus along the route to the [[:de:B\u00fcrgerbewegung|Citizens' Movement]] that within a couple of years had led to [[Die Wende|the end]] of the [[German Democratic Republic]] as a standalone state.<ref name=rev89RH>{{cite web |url=http://revolution89.de/?PID=static,Zeitzeugen,00220-Henrich,Index_en |title=Rolf Henrich|author=[[Ilko-Sascha Kowalczuk]]|publisher=[[:de:Robert-Havemann-Gesellschaft|Robert-Havemann-Gesellschaft e.V.]], Berlin|date=|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Life ==\n\n===Early years===\nHenrich was born in [[Magdeburg]], roughly equidistant between [[Hanover]] and [[Berlin]], and on the eastern side of the [[Inner German border|border]] that divided [[East Germany]] from [[West Germany]].   After [[Abitur|successfully completing]] his school career he went on to study Law at the [[Humboldt University of Berlin|Humboldt University]] in Berlin.   At the age of 20 he joined the country's ruling [[Socialist Unity Party of Germany|SED (party)]]<ref name=rev89RH/> and three years later he became an [[Informal collaborators (East Germany)|Informal collaborator (IM / ''Informeller Mitarbeiter'')]] for the [[Stasi|Ministry for State Security (Stasi)]].<ref name=rev89RH/> Between 1964 and 1969 he is listed as an IM in the Stasi files under the code name \"IM Streit\".<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenRH/>\n\n===The student===\nTwenty years later he would describe himself at age 20 as having joined the [[Socialist Unity Party of Germany|SED]] \"out of conviction\":  \"Back then\", he later recalled, he was \"even a bit fanatical\"<ref name=spiegel131989/><ref>\"[ich war]...begeisterter [[Free German Youth|FDJler]]...Ich war damals sogar ein bi\u00dfchen fanatisch.</ref> A powerful adumbration of future disenchantment with the East German regime nevertheless came in 1968, in the context of student discussions of the [[Prague Spring]]<ref name=BerKurRH>{{cite web |url=http://www.berliner-kurier.de/kiez-stadt/meine-wende--rolf-henrich--stell-dich-auf--die-seite-derer--auf-die-alle-mit--dem-finger-zeigen-,7169128,28347830,item,0.html|title=Meine Wende: Rolf Henrich \"Stell dich auf die Seite derer, auf die alle mit dem Finger zeigen\"|author=Gundula Mieke|publisher=[[Berliner Kurier]]|date=8 September 2014|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref> when he was officially reprimanded for \"revisionism\" and \"psychologizing the law\",<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenRH/> and suffered the withdrawal of a previously agreed research scholarship.<ref name=LeMORH>{{cite web |url=http://hdg.de/lemo/html/biografien/HenrichRolf/index.html|title= Rolf Henrich: Jurist|publisher=Stiftung Haus der Geschichte der Bundesrepublik Deutschland , [[Bonn]]|author=|date=|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref> He was also required to change the subject of his dissertation, now addressing the subject \"The next tasks of Soviet power\" (''\"Die n\u00e4chsten Aufgaben der Sowjetmacht\"''):  he nevertheless accomplished his own task, receiving his degree-diploma with a top grade.<ref name=spiegel131989/>\n\n===The young lawyer===\nAfter receiving his Law degree Henrich went on to perform his [[Military service]] in the [[National People's Army]] before taking a post as a research assistant at the prestigious [[:de:Deutsche Akademie f\u00fcr Staats- und Rechtswissenschaft|\"Walter Ulbricht\" German Legal Academy]] (as it was known at the time) in the [[Babelsberg]] quarter of [[Potsdam]].<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenRH/> In 1973 he set himself up as a lawyer in [[Eisenh\u00fcttenstadt]].   Here he supported [[Socialist Unity Party of Germany|The Party]] within the local \"Collective of Lawyers\" (''\"Kollegium der Rechtsanw\u00e4lte\"'') as [[Socialist Unity Party of Germany#Party Secretaries|Party Secretary]].<ref name=BerZeiRH01>{{cite web |url=http://www.berliner-zeitung.de/archiv/der-regimekritiker-und-anwalt-rolf-henrich-ueber-den-niedergang-des-sed-regimes-und-die-frage--warum-die-ddr-kein-rechtsstaat-war-der-despot-war-nur-noch-ein-phantom,10810590,10678382.html|title=Der Despot war nur noch ein Phantom:  Der Regimekritiker und Anwalt Rolf Henrich \u00fcber den Niedergang des SED-Regimes und die Frage, warum die DDR kein Rechtsstaat war|publisher= [[Berliner Zeitung]] (online)|author=[[:de:Adelbert Reif|Adelbert Reif]]|date=9 November 2009|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref> During this period he also undertook further studies, almost certainly of a political nature, at the regional party academy in [[Frankfurt (Oder)|Frankfurt (on the River Oder)]].<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenRH/>\n\n===Growing disenchantment===\nThe arrest of [[Rudolf Bahro]] in 1977 affected Henrich deeply<ref name=ZeitRH>{{cite web | url=http://www.zeit.de/1989/15/anders-als-bahro|title=Anders als Bahro: Ein Buch brachte dem DDR-Anwalt Rolf Henrich Berufsverbot ein |author= [[:de:Marlies Menge|Marlies Menge]]|publisher= [[Die Zeit]] (online)|date= 7 April 1989|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref> and he slowly became increasingly disillusioned with the East German regime and its Soviet-style Socialism,<ref name=LeMORH/> composing several highly critical essays (which remained unpublished).<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenRH/> He would later recall his disenchantment, which had set in and then developed ever since he started to practice in [[Eisenh\u00fcttenstadt]], with the way the law was applied in the [[German Democratic Republic]].<ref name=spiegel131989/> Nevertheless, Rolf Henrich remained a relatively discrete dissident through the early 1980s.   He himself later spoke of the need he had experienced slowly to free himself from the old dogmatism as a laborious process of internal conflict.<ref name=spiegel131989/><ref>\"Ich mu\u00dfte mich erst langsam aus dem Dogmatismus befreien, das war ein m\u00fchsamer Proze\u00df innerer Auseinandersetzung.\"</ref> He did, however, attract the interest of the [[Stasi|Ministry for State Security]] whose principal office in [[Eisenh\u00fcttenstadt]] was in the Bergstra\u00dfe (\"Mountain Street\"), close to his own office.<ref name=spiegel131989/> For approximately two years, starting in 1987, the camera installed to monitor people entering and leaving the Ministry was positioned so that it could periodically swing round and point directly at Henrich's desk, through his office window across the road.<ref name=spiegel131989>{{ cite web |url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-13495376.html |title=Die Wahrheit \u00f6ffentlich machen Ein fr\u00fcherer Parteisekret\u00e4r rechnet mit dem SED-System ab Der SED steht, rechtzeitig zur 40-Jahr-Feier der DDR, ein neuer Dissident ins Haus. Elf Jahre nach Bahro klagt ein Genosse die Parteif\u00fchrung \u00f6ffentlich an, sie halte sich nur mit Hilfe eines brutalen und allgegenw\u00e4rtigen Polizeiapparates an der Macht, die Stasi sei \"der Garant der Sozialversicherung\" f\u00fcr die Gerontokraten im Politb\u00fcro|publisher=[[Der Spiegel]] (online)|date=27 March 1989|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Into the limelight===\nHenrich's public profile was greatly raised with the publication in April 1989 of his book \"The Custodial State. On the Failure of Real-life Socialism\" (''\"Der vormundschaftliche Staat. Vom Versagen des real existierenden Sozialismus\"'')<ref name=DieVorStaRH/> There was at this time no question of anything so critical of the regime being published in [[East Germany]]: the book was published in [[West Germany]]<ref name=LeMORH/> where it received wide coverage in the broadcast and print media.<ref name=spiegel131989/> The book's publication evidently came as a surprise to the authorities.<ref name=rev89RH/> It presented a devastating and detailed criticism of a state where socialism had not progressed beyond the \"larval stage\" (''\"Sozialismus im Larvenstadium\"'') and the [[Stasi|security services]] felt free to operate outside the law.<ref name=spiegel131989/> In some ways it was a conscious follow-up to \"The Alternative\",<ref name=spiegel351977>{{cite web|title=Das trifft den Parteiapparat ins Herz. Ein SED-Funktion\u00e4r kritisiert den DDR-Sozialismus|language=German|trans-title=That's gonna hit the heart of the party. An SED functionary criticises GDR socialism.|date=22 August 1977|accessdate=27 January 2015|publisher=[[Der Spiegel]] (online)|url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-40763980.html}}</ref> the publication of which in 1977 had led to [[Rudolf Bahro|its author's]] arrest and subsequent deportation, but twelve years on Rolf Heinrich was much more analytically pessimistic about the way ahead for Socialism in the German Democratic Republic than Rudolf Bahro had been.<ref name=spiegel131989/> In East Germany Henrich was expelled from the ruling SED (party) and excluded from the \"Collective of Lawyers\" (''\"Kollegium der Rechtsanw\u00e4lte\"'')<ref name=BerKurRH/> which effectively terminated, for the time being, his legal career in [[Eisenh\u00fcttenstadt]].   The widespread assumption was that Rolf Henrich, like Bahro, would now be arrested and then deported or \"[[:de:H\u00e4ftlingsfreikauf|sold]]\" to [[West Germany|the west]].<ref name=spiegel131989/> That did not happen this time, however, possibly because behind the scenes the East Germany leadership hardliners were themselves struggling with a loss of self-confidence resulting from the [[Perestroika|political loosening]] now under way in the [[Soviet Union]] itself.<ref name=spiegelperestroika>{{ cite web |url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/ende-der-ddr-gorbatschow-war-an-stasi-uebernahme-durch-kgb-interessiert-a-654408.html|title= Ende der DDR: Gorbatschow war an Stasi-\u00dcbernahme durch KGB interessiert: Skurriles vom Untergang der DDR: Nach SPIEGEL-Informationen wollte Michail Gorbatschow im Jahr 1990, dass der KGB die Auslandsspionage der Stasi und das gesamte IM-Netz \u00fcbernimmt. Die sowjetische Bestandsgarantie f\u00fcr die DDR hat der damalige Kreml-Chef schon vor dem Untergang des Landes widerrufen.|publisher=[[Der Spiegel]] (online)|author=|date=10 October 2009|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref> Another explanation is that the regime was aware of the scale of the publicity Heinrich's book had already received both within and outside the German Democratic Republic and did not arrest him \"for political reasons\".<ref name=rev89RH/>\n\n===New Forum===\nEarly in September 1989, at [[Gr\u00fcnheide (Mark)|Gr\u00fcnheide]], Rolf Henrich was one of the 30 signatories of the founding proclamation that gave birth to the [[New Forum]] movement.   By the end of 1989 more than 200,000 had signed the proclamation despite New Forum having been identified by the East German [[Socialist Unity Party of Germany|governing party]] as illegal.   By this time, in any event, [[Die Wende|the Berlin wall]] had been breached by demonstrators on the eastern side early in November 1989, and when it became clear that the [[Group of Soviet Forces in Germany|fraternal Soviet troops]] had no instructions to prevent people from crossing it, the gate was seen to have been left open for a [[German reunification|reunification]] process that now appeared unstoppable.   \n{{Quote box|align=right|width=40%|\n:::'''Rolf Henrich: Published Works'''\n* ''Der vormundschaftliche Staat. Vom Versagen des real existierenden Sozialismus.'' Rowohlt Verlag Hamburg 1989, {{ISBN|3-499-12536-6}}\n* ''Gewalt und Form in einer vulkanischen Welt, Aufs\u00e4tze 1991\u201396.'' Berlin 1996, {{ISBN|3-932458-01-X}}\n* ''Die Schlinge.'' Eichborn Verlag Frankfurt/Main 2001, {{ISBN|3-8218-0707-5}} (his first novel)\n}}\nAs part of that process, between December 1989 and March 1990 a [[:de:Runder Tisch|Round Table forum]] was convened to work through the practical steps needed for German reunification.   Rolf Henrich participated in the Round Table discussions on behalf of [[New Forum]].<ref name=BiographischeDatenbankenRH/> Henrich set himself two principal tasks within the process.   The hated [[Stasi|Ministry for State Security]] had to be abolished.   There had been some suggestion that the institution might be reconfigured as a new \"National Security Agency\" (''\"Amt f\u00fcr Nationale Sicherheit\"'').   For Henrich, that would have been a mere re-labeling and as such totally unacceptable.<ref name=BerKurRH/> His second task was to help draft and enact a new election law for [[East Germany]], and to set a date for a democratically configured election to take place.<ref name=BerKurRH/> On 18 March 1990 the first, and as matters turned out, last, free [[1990 East German general election|parliamentary election]] in the history of the [[German Democratic Republic]] was held.   After this Rolf Henrich was satisfied that his own contribution to the Round Table exercise had been successfully completed.<ref name=BerKurRH/> In November 1989 the de facto ban that seven months earlier had prevented him from working as a lawyer had been revoked and he was by now free to return to work at his lawyer's office in [[Eisenh\u00fcttenstadt]].<ref name=LeMORH/>\n\n===Career options===\nHenrich later told an interviewer that [[Manfred Gerlach]], who had been the East German head of state between 3 December 1989 and 18 March 1990, had offered him a job as President of the [[Supreme Court of East Germany|country's Supreme Court]], but Henrich turned down that job along with an invitation to take a government post as secretary of state in the Ministry of Justice.   Henrich evidently thought he might have independence issues or become a \"figleaf\" with a high-profile post in the East German judicial-political establishment.  To maximize legitimacy, such jobs should go to an \"outsider\".<ref name=BerKurRH/>\n\nThere had also been a project involving the [[Gruner + Jahr]] publishing conglomerate to set up a pan-regional daily newspaper called \"Die Ostdeutsche\", based on the model of the highly successful [[S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung]].   That project failed because the newspaper market turned out to be overcrowded already.<ref name=BerKurRH/>\n\n[[German reunification]] formally took place in October 1990 and Rolf Henrich returned to his life as a provincial lawyer in [[Eisenh\u00fcttenstadt]].   His public profile never entirely vanished, however:  he continued to give occasional press interviews and to publish the occasional book.   In the courts he has worked as a defense lawyer in controversial cases including those involving former East German border guards charged in connection with shootings at the [[Berlin Wall]].<ref name=rev89RH/>\n\n==Awards and honours==\n* 2000 [[:de:Deutscher Nationalpreis|German National prize]] of the [[:de:Deutsche Nationalstiftung|German National Foundation]]<ref name=LeMORH/> (joint winner)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Henrich, Rolf}}\n[[Category:German lawyers]]\n[[Category:East German dissidents]]\n[[Category:Socialist Unity Party of Germany members]]\n[[Category:New Forum (East Germany) members]]\n[[Category:Social Democratic Party of Germany politicians]]\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:German male writers]]\n[[Category:People of the Stasi]]\n", "name_user": "Quebec99", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix duplicate ref names \u2013You can help!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rolf_Henrich"}
{"title_page": "Declan Meagher", "text_new": "{{short description|Irish obstetrician (1921-208)}}\nDr. '''Declan J Meagher''' was an Irish obstetrician, Master of the National Maternity Hospital, Dublin, and a champion of women's reproductive health.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fitzgerald|first=Muiris|last2=Murphy|first2=John F|date=30 January 2020|title=Declan J Meagher|url=https://www.bmj.com/content/368/bmj.m360|journal=British Medical Journal|volume=368|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix = Doctor\n| name             = Declan J Meagher\n| known_for        = {{hlist|[[Women's Health]]|[[Obstetrics]]}}\n| office           = Master of National Maternity Hospital\n| term_start       = 1970\n| term_end         = 1976\n| successor        = Dermot W MacDonald\n| succeeded        = Kieran O'Driscoll\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1921|03|21}}\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|2019|11|03|1921|03|21}}\n| death_place      = Dublin, Ireland\n| birth_place      = [[Ferbane, County Offaly]], Ireland\n| image            = PortraitDJM.png\n| caption          = Meagher in 1980\n}}\nIn 1963, Meagher set up one of the country's first family planning clinics. This was a time when most women in Ireland lived in poverty, had a large number of children and suffered from high childbirth mortality rates.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/health-family/doctors-remain-central-protagonists-in-state-s-reproductive-health-history-1.3658422|title=Doctors remain central protagonists in State's reproductive health history|last=Shannon|first=June|date=16 October 2018|website=The Irish Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref> The Irish Catholic Church, which was heavily involved in healthcare through the ownership of hospitals and schools, imposed conservative views on family planning and contraception. It had most recently prevented the [[Mother and Child Scheme]] to come into force. \n\nMeagher, who by 1970, had become Master of the [[National Maternity Hospital, Dublin|National Maternity Hospital]] in Dublin, one of the largest maternity hospitals in Europe, sought to reduce perinatal mortality by implementing a new approach to the management of [[childbirth]]. He did so by giving a greater role to midwives, providing additional support for mothers and reducing prolonged labour.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/people/declan-meagher-obituary-childbirth-pioneer-who-championed-irish-family-planning-1.4090822|title=Declan Meagher obituary: childbirth pioneer who championed Irish family planning|website=The Irish Times|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Salhan|first=Sudha|url=https://books.google.com/?id=RXSJDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA5&lpg=PA5&dq=meagher+dublin+o'driscoll#v=onepage&q=bishop%20meagher%20dublin%20o'driscoll&f=false|title=Textbook of Obstetrics|date=2016-08-30|publisher=JP Medical Ltd|isbn=978-93-85891-79-3|language=en}}</ref> \"The Dublin Experience\" helped usher in the modern era of Irish obstetrics<ref>{{Cite journal|last=J S|first=Scott|date=28 March 1981|title=Dublin Deliveries|url=https://www.bmj.com/content/282/6269/1064|journal=British Medical Journal|volume=282|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Corcoran|first=Mary|url=http://mural.maynoothuniversity.ie/610/1/Childbirth.pdf|title=Irish Sociological Chronicles|publisher=Institute of Public Administration|year=1999|isbn=1902448693|location=|pages=247\u2013259}}</ref> and led to the development of a clinical package of care now internationally known as \"active management of labour\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=O'Driscoll|first1=K.|last2=Meagher|first2=D.|last3=Boylan|first3=P.|date=1996-03-21|title=A Clinical Trial of Active Management of Labor|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|volume=334|issue=12|pages=797\u2013799|doi=10.1056/NEJM199603213341212|issn=0028-4793|pmid=8592558}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Neilson|first=J. P.|last2=Lavender|first2=T.|last3=Quenby|first3=S.|last4=Wray|first4=S.|date=2003-12-01|title=Obstructed labour - Reducing maternal death and disability during pregnancy|journal=British Medical Bulletin|language=en|volume=67|issue=1|pages=191\u2013204|doi=10.1093/bmb/ldg018|pmid=14711764|issn=0007-1420}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Myr|first=Rachel|date=2019-08-18|title=Reason for Active Management|url=https://www.bmj.com/rapid-response/2011/10/29/reason-active-management}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aims.org.uk/journal/item/active-management-of-labour|title=Active Management of Labour {{!}} AIMS|website=www.aims.org.uk|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref> \n\nAfter his career at the National Maternity Hospital,  Meagher took over as Director General of the Holy Family Hospital in Bethlehem, in the West Bank. There, with the Order of Malta and the European Union, he helped build Palestine's first maternity ward, introduced maternity training programs for local doctors and midwives, and set up rural maternity care clinics for Palestinian women.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/wren-boys-party-raises-funds-for-bethlehem-hospital-26025330.html|title=Wren Boys' party raises funds for Bethlehem hospital|website=independent|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.orderofmalta.int/humanitarian-medical-works/bethlehems-hospital/|title=Bethlehem's Hospital|website=Order of Malta|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref> Meagher also represented Ireland on the council of the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists in London, which he used to share maternity care practices and build ties between the Republic of Ireland and Northern Ireland. \n\nMeagher co-authored with  Kieran O'Driscoll, ''The Active Management of Labour'', which is used in medical school curricula in Europe, Australia, Canada, Great Britain, and the United States.<ref>{{Cite book|last=O'Driscoll, Kieran.|title=Active management of labour : the Dublin experience|date=2003|publisher=Mosby|others=Meagher, Declan., Robson, Michael.|isbn=978-0-7234-3202-9|edition=4th|location=Edinburgh|oclc=54966842}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elsevier.com/books/active-management-of-labour/odriscoll/978-0-7234-3202-9|title=Active Management of Labour - 4th Edition|website=www.elsevier.com|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Meagher, Declan}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from County Offaly]]\n[[Category:Irish obstetricians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Irish obstetrician (1921-208)}}\nDr. '''Declan J Meagher''' was an Irish obstetrician, Master of the National Maternity Hospital, Dublin, and a champion of women's reproductive health.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fitzgerald|first=Muiris|last2=Murphy|first2=John F|date=30 January 2020|title=Declan J Meagher|url=https://www.bmj.com/content/368/bmj.m360|journal=British Medical Journal|volume=368|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix = Doctor\n| name             = Declan J Meagher\n| known_for        = {{hlist|[[Women's Health]]|[[Obstetrics]]}}\n| office           = Master of National Maternity Hospital\n| term_start       = 1970\n| term_end         = 1976\n| successor        = Dermot W MacDonald\n| succeeded        = Kieran O'Driscoll\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1921|03|21}}\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|2019|11|03|1921|03|21}}\n| death_place      = Dublin, Ireland\n| birth_place      = [[Ferbane, County Offaly]], Ireland\n| image            = PortraitDJM.png\n| caption          = Meagher in 1980\n}}\nIn 1963, Meagher set up one of the country's first family planning clinics. This was a time when most women in Ireland lived in poverty, had a large number of children and suffered from high childbirth mortality rates.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/health-family/doctors-remain-central-protagonists-in-state-s-reproductive-health-history-1.3658422|title=Doctors remain central protagonists in State's reproductive health history|last=Shannon|first=June|date=16 October 2018|website=The Irish Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref> The Irish Catholic Church, which was heavily involved in healthcare through the ownership of hospitals and schools, imposed conservative views on family planning and contraception. It had most recently prevented the [[Mother and Child Scheme]] to come into force. \n\nMeagher, who by 1970, had become Master of the [[National Maternity Hospital, Dublin|National Maternity Hospital]] in Dublin, one of the largest maternity hospitals in Europe, sought to reduce perinatal mortality by implementing a new approach to the management of [[childbirth]]. He did so by giving a greater role to midwives, providing additional support for mothers and reducing prolonged labour.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/people/declan-meagher-obituary-childbirth-pioneer-who-championed-irish-family-planning-1.4090822|title=Declan Meagher obituary: childbirth pioneer who championed Irish family planning|website=The Irish Times|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Salhan|first=Sudha|url=https://books.google.com/?id=RXSJDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA5&lpg=PA5&dq=meagher+dublin+o'driscoll#v=onepage&q=bishop%20meagher%20dublin%20o'driscoll&f=false|title=Textbook of Obstetrics|date=2016-08-30|publisher=JP Medical Ltd|isbn=978-93-85891-79-3|language=en}}</ref> \"The Dublin Experience\" helped usher in the modern era of Irish obstetrics<ref>{{Cite journal|last=J S|first=Scott|date=28 March 1981|title=Dublin Deliveries|url=https://www.bmj.com/content/282/6269/1064|journal=British Medical Journal|volume=282|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Corcoran|first=Mary|url=http://mural.maynoothuniversity.ie/610/1/Childbirth.pdf|title=Irish Sociological Chronicles|publisher=Institute of Public Administration|year=1999|isbn=1902448693|location=|pages=247\u2013259}}</ref> and led to the development of a clinical package of care now internationally known as \"active of management of labour\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=O'Driscoll|first1=K.|last2=Meagher|first2=D.|last3=Boylan|first3=P.|date=1996-03-21|title=A Clinical Trial of Active Management of Labor|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|volume=334|issue=12|pages=797\u2013799|doi=10.1056/NEJM199603213341212|issn=0028-4793|pmid=8592558}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Neilson|first=J. P.|last2=Lavender|first2=T.|last3=Quenby|first3=S.|last4=Wray|first4=S.|date=2003-12-01|title=Obstructed labour - Reducing maternal death and disability during pregnancy|journal=British Medical Bulletin|language=en|volume=67|issue=1|pages=191\u2013204|doi=10.1093/bmb/ldg018|pmid=14711764|issn=0007-1420}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Myr|first=Rachel|date=2019-08-18|title=Reason for Active Management|url=https://www.bmj.com/rapid-response/2011/10/29/reason-active-management}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aims.org.uk/journal/item/active-management-of-labour|title=Active Management of Labour {{!}} AIMS|website=www.aims.org.uk|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref> \n\nAfter his career at the National Maternity Hospital,  Meagher took over as Director General of the Holy Family Hospital in Bethlehem, in the West Bank. There, with the Order of Malta and the European Union, he helped build Palestine's first maternity ward, introduced maternity training programs for local doctors and midwives, and set up rural maternity care clinics for Palestinian women.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/wren-boys-party-raises-funds-for-bethlehem-hospital-26025330.html|title=Wren Boys' party raises funds for Bethlehem hospital|website=independent|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.orderofmalta.int/humanitarian-medical-works/bethlehems-hospital/|title=Bethlehem's Hospital|website=Order of Malta|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref> Meagher also represented Ireland on the council of the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists in London, which he used to share maternity care practices and build ties between the Republic of Ireland and Northern Ireland. \n\nMeagher co-authored with  Kieran O'Driscoll, ''The Active Management of Labour'', which is used in medical school curricula in Europe, Australia, Canada, Great Britain, and the United States.<ref>{{Cite book|last=O'Driscoll, Kieran.|title=Active management of labour : the Dublin experience|date=2003|publisher=Mosby|others=Meagher, Declan., Robson, Michael.|isbn=978-0-7234-3202-9|edition=4th|location=Edinburgh|oclc=54966842}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elsevier.com/books/active-management-of-labour/odriscoll/978-0-7234-3202-9|title=Active Management of Labour - 4th Edition|website=www.elsevier.com|access-date=2019-08-18}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Meagher, Declan}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from County Offaly]]\n[[Category:Irish obstetricians]]\n", "name_user": "GMTL404", "label": "safe", "comment": "deleted \"of\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Declan_Meagher"}
